    "According to [47], a Markov state ρ XY E (for two sources X, Y, and the adversary's system E, with the Markov conditions discussed in Theorem 4) can be decomposed into product states (Equation ( 11)) asρ XY E = t p(t)ρ t XE t X ⊗ ρ t Y E t Y (12)where t runs over a finite alphabet with probability distribution p(t), andH E = t H E t X ⊗ H E t Yis the Hilbert space of E (the quantum system held by the adversary).",
    "Using this decomposition, we can rewrite Equation (6) asρ Ext(X,Y)E -u Z ⊗ ρ E 1 = ∥Ext ⊗ I E (ρ XY E) -u Z ⊗ ρ E ∥ 1 (13) = Ext ⊗ I E t p(t)ρ t XE t X ⊗ ρ t Y E t Y -u Z ⊗ t ρ t E t X ⊗ ρ t E t Y 1 (14) = t p(t) Ext ⊗ I E ρ t XE t X ⊗ ρ t Y E t Y -u Z ⊗ ρ t E t X ⊗ ρ t E t Y 1(15)≤ t p(t)2 (n 2 -k 2)/2 ϵ = 2 (n 2 -k 2)/2 ϵ (16)where Ext(X, Y) denotes the application of the extractor on X, Y, which is also understood as the CPTP map Ext ⊗ I E on ρ XY E, and u Z is the maximally mixed state over the output Z of the extractor.",
    "In the last inequality, we have used the fact that the extractor is already quantum-proof in the product source model, meaning that, Ext ⊗I E ρ t XE t X ⊗ ρ t Y E t Y -u Z ⊗ ρ t E t X ⊗ ρ t E t Y 1 ≤ 2 (n 2 -k 2)/2 ϵ for all t, noting that the ccq-state ρ t XE t X ⊗ ρ t Y E t Y satisfies H ∞ (X|E) ≥ k 1 and H ∞ (Y |E) for any t, given H ∞ (X|E) ≥ k 1 and H ∞ (Y |E) for ρ XY E.In both Theorems 3, 4 and Corollary 1, one has the option to lift an extractor to the Markov model whilst maintaining whether it is strong or not (a strong extractor will be strong in the Markov model, a weak one will remain weak).",
    "We have indicated this option by putting strong in parenthesis in the statements.The Markov model is particularly relevant in protocols for randomness amplification [18,48] and in quantum key distribution (QKD) 8.",
